SIMPLE: nasal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nasal
<hw>Na"sal</hw> <pr>(n⟦amac⟧"z⟦ait⟧l)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., from
L. <ets>nasus</ets> the nose. See <er>Nose</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the nose.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Phon.)</fld> <def>Having a quality imparted by
means of the nose; and specifically, made by lowering the soft palate,
in some cases with closure of the oral passage, the voice thus issuing
(wholly or partially) through the nose, as in the consonants <it>m</it>,
<it>n</it>, <it>ng</it> (see <xex>Guide to Pronunciation</xex>,
⟦sect⟧⟦sect⟧ 20, 208); characterized by resonance in the nasal passage;
<as>as, a <ex>nasal</ex> vowel; a <ex>nasal</ex>
utterance.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Nasal bones</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>two bones
of the skull, in front of the frontals.</cd> -- <col><b>Nasal
index</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>in the skull, the ratio of the
transverse breadth of the anterior nasal aperture to the height from the
base of the aperture to the nasion, which latter distance is taken as
the standard, equal to 100.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nasal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nasal
<hw>Na"sal</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An elementary sound
which is uttered through the nose, or through both the nose and the
mouth simultaneously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>A medicine that operates through
the nose; an errhine.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor)</fld> <def>Part of a helmet projecting
to protect the nose; a <altname>nose guard</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <def>One of the nasal bones.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A plate, or scale, on the nose of
a fish, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nasalis</ent>⟦br⟧
